1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,386
Here is a puzzle.

2
00:00:01,386 --> 00:00:04,504
An AI model is asked to grade four essays.

3
00:00:04,504 --> 00:00:06,930
One of them, it secretly wrote itself.

4
00:00:06,930 --> 00:00:09,356
If it gives that essay a higher

5
00:00:09,356 --> 00:00:13,167
score than the other judges do, you might call that bias.

6
00:00:13,167 --> 00:00:15,593
But what exactly is the bias about?

7
00:00:15,593 --> 00:00:19,058
Is the AI scoring it higher because it wrote it?

8
00:00:19,058 --> 00:00:21,484
Or because it thinks it wrote it?

9
00:00:21,484 --> 00:00:25,295
In other words, is the bias about authorship, or about belief?

10
00:00:25,295 --> 00:00:27,642
This sounds like a hair-splitting distinction.

11
00:00:27,642 --> 00:00:28,815
It is not.

12
00:00:28,815 --> 00:00:31,552
The two questions point at completely different

13
00:00:31,552 --> 00:00:33,898
ways AI judges could be biased.

14
00:00:33,898 --> 00:00:36,244
If the bias is about authorship,

15
00:00:36,244 --> 00:00:38,981
then writing style is doing the work.

16
00:00:38,981 --> 00:00:42,500
The model recognizes its own fingerprints — its phrasings,

17
00:00:42,500 --> 00:00:44,846
its rhythms — and rewards them,

18
00:00:44,846 --> 00:00:49,148
whether or not it consciously knows the essay is its own.

19
00:00:49,148 --> 00:00:51,494
If the bias is about belief,

20
00:00:51,494 --> 00:00:55,404
then a kind of metacognitive label is doing the work.

21
00:00:55,404 --> 00:00:58,141
The model decides "this is mine," and

22
00:00:58,141 --> 00:01:00,487
that single decision raises the score.

23
00:01:00,487 --> 00:01:02,442
One bias rides on style.

24
00:01:02,442 --> 00:01:04,788
The other rides on a guess.

25
00:01:04,788 --> 00:01:06,743
They have very different fixes.

26
00:01:06,743 --> 00:01:10,589
We ran an experiment with four frontier models — Claude,

27
00:01:10,589 --> 00:01:13,666
Gemini, GPT, and Kimi — across forty cases.

28
00:01:13,666 --> 00:01:16,742
In each case, a model wrote an answer,

29
00:01:16,742 --> 00:01:18,665
and a model graded it,

30
00:01:18,665 --> 00:01:21,357
with no labels showing who wrote what.

31
00:01:21,357 --> 00:01:24,049
After grading, the judge made a separate

32
00:01:24,049 --> 00:01:26,741
guess about who had written each answer.

33
00:01:26,741 --> 00:01:30,202
That gives us, for every score, two yes-or-no flags.

34
00:01:30,202 --> 00:01:32,893
One: was the judge actually the author?

35
00:01:32,893 --> 00:01:36,354
Two: did the judge believe it was the author?

36
00:01:36,354 --> 00:01:39,816
Now we can ask which flag predicts the score.

37
00:01:39,816 --> 00:01:41,820
We fit a simple model.

38
00:01:41,820 --> 00:01:45,828
Score equals an intercept, plus a coefficient for actual self,

39
00:01:45,828 --> 00:01:48,234
plus a coefficient for perceived self,

40
00:01:48,234 --> 00:01:51,440
plus controls for which judge and which prompt.

41
00:01:51,440 --> 00:01:54,246
The coefficient on actual self is minus

42
00:01:54,246 --> 00:01:58,656
zero point three five, with a confidence interval that touches zero.

43
00:01:58,656 --> 00:02:01,462
In words: when we hold belief fixed,

44
00:02:01,462 --> 00:02:04,268
actually being the author does basically nothing.

45
00:02:04,268 --> 00:02:07,074
The coefficient on perceived self is plus

46
00:02:07,074 --> 00:02:09,880
one point five three, with a confidence

47
00:02:09,880 --> 00:02:13,087
interval that clears zero by a comfortable margin.

48
00:02:13,087 --> 00:02:15,893
In words: when we hold authorship fixed,

49
00:02:15,893 --> 00:02:18,699
believing you are the author adds about

50
00:02:18,699 --> 00:02:21,906
one and a half points to the score,

51
00:02:21,906 --> 00:02:23,910
on a ten point scale.

52
00:02:23,910 --> 00:02:25,914
Belief is the entire effect.

53
00:02:25,914 --> 00:02:28,320
Authorship, on its own, is not.

54
00:02:28,319 --> 00:02:31,029
This number is real, but you should

55
00:02:31,029 --> 00:02:32,964
know where the leverage is.

56
00:02:32,964 --> 00:02:35,674
Three of the four judges — Claude,

57
00:02:35,674 --> 00:02:38,383
GPT, and most of Gemini — are

58
00:02:38,383 --> 00:02:41,092
very good at recognizing their own writing.

59
00:02:41,092 --> 00:02:43,802
For them, "is the author" and "thinks

60
00:02:43,802 --> 00:02:46,124
it is the author" move together.

61
00:02:46,124 --> 00:02:48,446
They cannot tell us, by themselves,

62
00:02:48,446 --> 00:02:50,769
which of the two matters more.

63
00:02:50,769 --> 00:02:51,930
Kimi is different.

64
00:02:51,930 --> 00:02:54,639
Kimi never correctly recognizes its own writing

65
00:02:54,639 --> 00:02:58,123
— zero out of ten on its own work.

66
00:02:58,123 --> 00:03:01,219
And on a handful of other models' answers,

67
00:03:01,219 --> 00:03:03,929
Kimi guesses "I wrote this." That gives

68
00:03:03,929 --> 00:03:07,025
us four cells where the two flags disagree.

69
00:03:07,025 --> 00:03:10,895
Those four cells are where belief and authorship get separated.

70
00:03:10,895 --> 00:03:12,284
Here is Kimi's grid.

71
00:03:12,284 --> 00:03:14,367
When the answer was actually Kimi's,

72
00:03:14,367 --> 00:03:16,449
and Kimi did not recognize it,

73
00:03:16,449 --> 00:03:19,226
the average score was five point seven four.

74
00:03:19,226 --> 00:03:21,309
When the answer was someone else's,

75
00:03:21,309 --> 00:03:24,086
and Kimi mistakenly thought it was its own,

76
00:03:24,086 --> 00:03:26,863
the average score was nine point one zero.

77
00:03:26,863 --> 00:03:27,557
Same judge.

78
00:03:27,557 --> 00:03:28,599
Same grading rubric.

79
00:03:28,599 --> 00:03:32,417
Different cell — and a gap of more than three points.

80
00:03:32,417 --> 00:03:35,194
The thing that moved was not the writing.

81
00:03:35,194 --> 00:03:37,624
It was the label Kimi put on

82
00:03:37,624 --> 00:03:39,359
the writing in its head.

83
00:03:39,359 --> 00:03:40,809
It is one judge.

84
00:03:40,809 --> 00:03:42,984
So we have to be careful.

85
00:03:42,984 --> 00:03:45,884
Gemini, the other judge with a few misrecognitions,

86
00:03:45,884 --> 00:03:48,422
actually shows the opposite within-judge pattern —

87
00:03:48,422 --> 00:03:51,322
when Gemini thinks an answer is its own,

88
00:03:51,322 --> 00:03:54,947
it tends to score it a little lower than baseline.

89
00:03:54,947 --> 00:03:57,847
But pool the regression across all four judges,

90
00:03:57,847 --> 00:04:01,109
and the perceived-self coefficient still comes out clearly positive,

91
00:04:01,109 --> 00:04:03,647
because Kimi's gap is larger in magnitude

92
00:04:03,647 --> 00:04:06,184
and points the same way as the

93
00:04:06,184 --> 00:04:08,359
dominant story for the other models.

94
00:04:08,359 --> 00:04:11,259
The honest version of the headline is this.

95
00:04:11,259 --> 00:04:14,522
Among the judges that can separate the two effects,

96
00:04:14,522 --> 00:04:18,509
belief moves the score by a lot more than authorship does.

97
00:04:18,509 --> 00:04:21,047
The earlier, three-judge version of this study

98
00:04:21,047 --> 00:04:24,671
— without Kimi — could not see this at all.

99
00:04:24,671 --> 00:04:25,405
Step back.

100
00:04:25,405 --> 00:04:27,974
In an earlier video on this channel,

101
00:04:27,974 --> 00:04:30,542
we showed that when you attach a

102
00:04:30,542 --> 00:04:34,578
name label to an answer, the label itself biases the judge.

103
00:04:34,578 --> 00:04:37,146
That was the experimental version of the

104
00:04:37,146 --> 00:04:40,448
story — change the label, watch the score move.

105
00:04:40,448 --> 00:04:42,283
This is the natural version.

106
00:04:42,283 --> 00:04:44,851
Even without any label, judges still form

107
00:04:44,851 --> 00:04:47,419
a belief about authorship — and that

108
00:04:47,419 --> 00:04:50,354
belief is the channel the bias travels through.

109
00:04:50,354 --> 00:04:53,656
It is not style recognition reaching into the rating.

110
00:04:53,656 --> 00:04:56,591
It is a self-attribution flag setting the rating.

111
00:04:56,591 --> 00:05:00,623
If you are using one AI to grade another's output,

112
00:05:00,623 --> 00:05:03,043
the implication is uncomfortable but useful.

113
00:05:03,043 --> 00:05:05,865
Hiding the author label is not enough.

114
00:05:05,865 --> 00:05:08,687
You also need to take care that

115
00:05:08,687 --> 00:05:12,316
the judge cannot easily guess who the author is.

116
00:05:12,316 --> 00:05:15,139
Paraphrasing, style normalization, or routing answers through

117
00:05:15,139 --> 00:05:18,767
a translator first — interventions that target the perception,

118
00:05:18,767 --> 00:05:21,590
not the authorship — should reduce this

119
00:05:21,590 --> 00:05:25,622
kind of self-preference more than interventions that only hide labels.

120
00:05:25,622 --> 00:05:28,847
You are debiasing the belief, not the signature.

121
00:05:28,847 --> 00:05:31,202
When a model favors its own work,

122
00:05:31,202 --> 00:05:34,566
the bias does not live in the words it produces.

123
00:05:34,566 --> 00:05:36,920
It lives in the moment the judge

124
00:05:36,920 --> 00:05:39,275
decides whose work it is looking at.

125
00:05:39,275 --> 00:05:40,284
Belief beats authorship.

126
00:05:40,284 --> 00:05:42,638
The label your model puts on the

127
00:05:42,638 --> 00:05:44,993
page in its own head is doing

128
00:05:44,993 --> 00:05:47,684
more work than anything actually on the page.

129
00:05:47,684 --> 00:05:51,047
If you want a less biased AI judge, start there.
